    "title": "Integrative Close: SI Units in Circuit Analysis",
    "objective": "Synthesize the distinction between base and derived units by explaining the relationship between current, voltage, and power.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the electrical trade, you don't just see numbers; you see quantities that tell a story about a circuit's behavior. Understanding which units are fundamental 'base' building blocks and which are 'derived' through calculation is the mark of a professional electrician.",
      "This distinction is vital when verifying your results and ensuring your technical documentation is accurate. Using the correct SI terminology ensures that your calculations for power, energy, and circuit loading are technically sound and internationally recognised."
    ],
    "questionText": "A circuit has a current of 10 Amperes and a potential difference of 230 Volts, resulting in 2300 Watts of power. Explain the fundamental difference in how the 'Ampere' is classified compared to the 'Volt' and 'Watt' within the SI system, and identify which of these three specific units represents the 'rate' at which energy is being converted.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The Ampere is classified as a Base Unit (a fundamental building block).",
      "The Volt and the Watt are classified as Derived Units (calculated by combining other units).",
      "The Watt is the unit that represents the rate of energy conversion (Power)."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which unit is one of the seven fundamental 'primary colors' of measurement and which ones are 'mixed' from others."
  }
